ir affairs to church, commune, and themselves. With the aid of DEB, moneymaking was "Christianized" and Christianity was made more amenable to the pursuit of wealth. Although DEB is typically viewed exclusively as a scientifically neutral account of the flow of money through a firm, it remains as it was originally devised, a rhetorical argument.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAccountingxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aBookkeepingxHistory. 0aCapitalismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic ChurchxHistory. 0aEconomicsxReligious aspectsxCatholic ChurchxHistory. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482797423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482797/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles